63 5—920 form the polemical section of the book. Lucr. here seeks to disprove certain rival theories of the composition of matter maintained by other philosophers: these are (1) Heracleitus; (2) Empedocles; (3) Anaxagoras. Of these the first is treated most severely, because Heracleitus was to the Stoics what Democritus was to the Epicureans—the originator of their physical science, and the contest between the two schools was still keen in the time os Lucretius. In speaking of Empedocles, on the other hand, Lucr. uses the language os reverence and even os affection.
